.TH "qmi_txn_init" 9 "qmi_txn_init" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
qmi_txn_init \- allocate transaction id within the given QMI handle
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "int" qmi_txn_init
.BI "(struct qmi_handle *qmi "  ","
.BI "struct qmi_txn *txn "  ","
.BI "struct qmi_elem_info *ei "  ","
.BI "void *c_struct "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "qmi" 12
QMI handle
.IP "txn" 12
transaction context
.IP "ei" 12
description of how to decode a matching response (optional)
.IP "c_struct" 12
pointer to the object to decode the response into (optional)
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
This allocates a transaction id within the QMI handle. If \fIei\fP and \fIc_struct\fP
are specified any responses to this transaction will be decoded as described
by \fIei\fP into \fIc_struct\fP.

A client calling \fBqmi_txn_init\fP must call either \fBqmi_txn_wait\fP or
\fBqmi_txn_cancel\fP to free up the allocated resources.
.SH "RETURN"
Transaction id on success, negative errno on failure.
